In early 1948, following reports of strengthening "reactionary elements", Soviet operatives executed a coup d'Ã©tat in Czechoslovakia, the only Eastern Bloc state that the Soviets had permitted to retain democratic structures.[95] The public brutality of the coup shocked Western powers more than any event up to that point, set in motion a brief scare that war would occur and swept away the last vestiges of opposition to the Marshall Plan in the United States Congress.[96]
